Based on the XPS full-scan spectra (Fig. 4
                        ), B-CDs: C, 63.35%, N, 5.48%, O, 31.17%; R-CDs: C, 65.03%, N, 6.24%, O, 28.73%. The nitrogen content of R-CDs is higher, while the oxygen content is relatively low. Under the same conditions, the alkaline synthesis environment further aggravates the process of dehydration condensation, cross-linking and carbonization in the process of CDs synthesis, and at the same time makes more self-doping nitrogen to generate CDs (Table 2.). According to the C1s spectra (Fig. 4(b)), the peaks at 284.8 eV, 286.4 eV, 287.9 eV and 288.5 eV belong to C–C/C = C, C–N, C–O and C = O bonds [12], indicating that the CDs have the graphitized core and a great amount of hydroxyl and amide groups distribute on their surfaces. The N1s spectra (Fig. 4(c)) have two peaks corresponding to pyrrolic N and graphitic N [30,32,33], respectively. And the graphitic N in R-CDs is dominant compared to B-CDs (Table. 1

                        ). The O1s spectra of B-CDs can be divided into three peaks (531.7 eV, 532.6 eV, 533.4 eV), which correspond to C = O, C–O and C–O–C characteristic groups [34]. And the two peaks of the O1s spectra for R-CDs correspond to the existence of C = O and C–O characteristic groups [7]. The content of C–O bonds for B-CDs and R-CDs is 25.03% and 58.21% (Table. 3
                        ), respectively. It shows that the major factor impacting the multi-peak lightening of R-CDs is the specific oxygen-containing functional group, namely –OH, rather than the simple increase of the degree of surface oxidation.
